<br>
'No Ghoulbane,' smiled Tassius. 'Not today.'<br>
<br>
Tassisus watched across the steppe as a desperate, skeletal, undead soul wandered here and there. Its red eyes seeking the life and blood of others. Mercy would not be one of its founding principles if it found someone weak. Ghoulbane cursed its master's weakness and settled back in its sheath.<br>
<br>
The snow whipped across the plains. Icy winds tore at Tassius's ears. Everfrost was an unforgiving host. Short on courtesy. <br>
<br>
In his mind Tassius could hear his friend, Jeldar the Shaman speaking with him and Semdayen. They were all hunting the great prize of the plains. The mammoth.<br>
<br>
A beast the size of a building. With great goring tusks that could skewer a man like a steak on a stick. Matted hair covered its body. and the stench. Oh my god. It was like a walking pig farm. <br>
<br>
But the rewards were be deeply appreciated. Tassius's sword skills had been sharpened considerably by his exploits out here in the snow. And the tusks themselves fetched a pretty penny to those who were strong enough to carry them back to Halas. <br>
<br>
Tassius narrowed his eyes and look out through the snow. He strained his ears for the familiar sound in the distance. The footsteps like an earthquake. You often heard them before you saw them. Many a time he had used his ears to direct him to the beast. <br>
<br>
However sometimes this did not pay off. The Ice Giants, a fearsome adversary who would love to use Tass as a toothpick, had a very similiar footstep. On more than one occasion Tass had come bounding over a snow dune to find the grinning mania of a giant where a hairy mammoth should have been.<br>
<br>
Jeldar was telling them that other big game groups were arriving. We was worried we would lose our catch. Tassius began to narrow his thoughts in response when Sem beat him to it.<br>
<br>
'They are fools Jel. They sit by that platform and wait for the game. They will catch none. It is only by seeking the prey that you find it here.'<br>
<br>
Too true. Mammoth hunts were an exercise in co-ordinated catching, running and meeting. You split up. You find one. You hack at it to antagonise it and then run to a pre-agreed point for battle.<br>
<br>
There was nothing like the feel of a tusk on your arse to encourage you to take those longer strides through the snow. To know that behind you was something akin to a town hall covered in hair wishing to make a kebab out of you was very, very compelling.<br>
<br>
Tassius laughed to himself and tenderly pressed on some of the more recent scars in his back and rear. Oh yes. It was a very motivating experience. The pain brought him back to the now. He resumed his search.<br>
<br>
Tassius took a couple of strides forward and slide down a snowy bank onto the icy river. He edged across it uneasily. It would be difficult to run on this but he knew it was a favourite place for the beasts to emerge.<br>
<br>
And then he heard it...boom, boom, boom. The footsteps. He checked the sound. To his right. He swung round and spied it. A great mammoth. A smile came to Tassius's face and he charged.<br>
<br>
He was about fifteen yards from it when he began to sense there was something wrong. Something different about this mammoth. No matter. Tusk was tusk. He ploughed on. <br>
<br>
Tassius struck hard on the beast leg with his blade. The mammoth rounded and roared. A roar like no other like 100 trumpets at half speed and double the volume. It was then that Tass saw its eyes. It was insane. Spittle hung in great wads from its mouth. Its bulbous, yellow eyes rolled in its head as it struggled to pick Tassius out beneath.<br>
<br>
Tassius stumbled backwards and fell on his shield arm.<br>
<br>
'Lads. I think I have chanced upon the infamous tainted mammoth' screamed Tassius as he kicked himself backwards from under the mammoths diving tusks.<br>
<br>
'Great.' replied Sem, 'Bring it on.'<br>
'On my way.' said Jeldar ever calm.<br>
<br>
Tassisus's reply was lost as he was up-ended by the mammoth from the river to the bank. He was winded but not stupid. He was up and running in seconds. Sprinting back to the meeting point with the boom, boom, boom ringing in his ears.... <p>Tassius Vindenervis.<BR>
<BR>
'To spend ones time is easy, to give ones time demands a little more thought'<BR>
<BR>
